{"term": "2012", "caseName": "McBurney v. Young", "caseLink": "https://www.oyez.org/cases/2012/12-17", "caseTranscripts": [{"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - February 20, 2013", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/21398", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "We'll hear argument this morning first in Case 12-17, McBurney v. Young.", "start": 0, "stop": 6.32, "duration": 6.32}, {"text": "Mr. Gupta.", "start": 6.32, "stop": 7.57, "duration": 1.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, and may it please the Court:", "start": 7.57, "stop": 9.022, "duration": 1.45}, {"text": "All 50 States have public records laws.", "start": 9.022, "stop": 11.891, "duration": 2.87}, {"text": "47 of those States make access available to residents and nonresidents on equal terms.", "start": 11.891, "stop": 18.378, "duration": 6.49}, {"text": "Virginia, by contrast, enforces a discriminatory access policy, and because commercial requesters make up the vast majority of records requesters, out of State businesses bear the brunt of Virginia's policy--", "start": 18.378, "stop": 31.369, "duration": 12.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "When -- when was the first of those laws enacted, do you know?", "start": 31.369, "stop": 34.737, "duration": 3.37}, {"text": "I think it's -- I think it's in my adult lifetime that Florida was the first to enact a sunshine law.", "start": 34.737, "stop": 42.157, "duration": 7.42}, {"text": "Is that -- am I correct about that?", "start": 42.157, "stop": 43.843, "duration": 1.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's right.", "start": 43.843, "stop": 44.276, "duration": 0.43}, {"text": "All of these laws--", "start": 44.276, "stop": 44.476, "duration": 0.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "In the '60s.", "start": 44.476, "stop": 45.209, "duration": 0.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--In the '60s and the early '70s.", "start": 45.209, "stop": 48.045, "duration": 2.84}, {"text": "The Virginia law was enacted in 1968.", "start": 48.045, "stop": 50.58, "duration": 2.53}, {"text": "And we don't deny that--", "start": 50.58, "stop": 52.699, "duration": 2.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "And you say that's a fundamental -- that's a fundamental right covered by a Privileges and Immunities Clause, which nobody had until the 1960s.", "start": 52.699, "stop": 61.887, "duration": 9.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, to be clear, the modern transparency laws are new, but they sit on top of well-established common law rights to access that are based not on modern notions of transparency but on the right to secure property and other basic interests--", "start": 61.887, "stop": 76.564, "duration": 14.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "But those -- those rights still exist in this State, don't they?", "start": 76.564, "stop": 78.714, "duration": 2.15}, {"text": "Cannot you get records of deeds and whatever the common law would have covered?", "start": 78.714, "stop": 85.618, "duration": 6.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, it's true that -- that Virginia's law exempts deeds from its Freedom of Information law, but if I understand their position correctly, they would be entitled as a constitutional matter under their theory to preclude people from other States from accessing even deeds.", "start": 85.618, "stop": 101.377, "duration": 15.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I'll ask him -- I didn't understand that to be their position, but -- but I guess we can ask them.", "start": 101.377, "stop": 106.464, "duration": 5.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "My client, Mr. Hurlbert, is in the business of gathering property records for his clients.", "start": 106.464, "stop": 110.749, "duration": 4.28}, {"text": "Now, it's true that in Virginia, he could get the deed, but what he can't get and what he principally gathers for his clients are real estate tax assessment records, and those are a much richer storehouse of property-related information than simply the deed.", "start": 110.749, "stop": 125.359, "duration": 14.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Can you -- can you explain that business a little more fully than you did in the briefs?", "start": 125.359, "stop": 130.412, "duration": 5.05}, {"text": "He's in the business of collecting records from all the States about tax assessments.", "start": 130.412, "stop": 135.697, "duration": 5.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 135.697, "stop": 136.483, "duration": 0.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "And he -- and he does that for a client who could very well ask himself.", "start": 136.483, "stop": 143.22, "duration": 6.74}, {"text": "So what is the service that's being performed?", "start": 143.22, "stop": 145.839, "duration": 2.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, he -- you know, he doesn't just do the routine request.", "start": 145.839, "stop": 148.874, "duration": 3.03}, {"text": "These -- the large data companies are the ones who hire him.", "start": 148.874, "stop": 152.076, "duration": 3.2}, {"text": "And they -- if they're routine requests, they can do them themselves.", "start": 152.076, "stop": 156.897, "duration": 4.82}, {"text": "Although if they're not based in Virginia, they would still have to hire a Virginian to do it.", "start": 156.897, "stop": 161.182, "duration": 4.28}, {"text": "But they bring him in when there's some flaw in the -- the routine process where the -- the State is being recalcitrant, or the local official is being recalcitrant.", "start": 161.182, "stop": 170.454, "duration": 9.27}, {"text": "And he's an expert in being able to gather these -- these records, and knowing the process is knowing what he's allowed to do and what he's not allowed to do.", "start": 170.454, "stop": 179.326, "duration": 8.87}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "All -- all he has to do is get somebody from -- from Virginia to ask for him, right?", "start": 179.326, "stop": 182.862, "duration": 3.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, he could hire someone from Virginia to do that, but that's -- you know, that's sort of precisely what the--", "start": 182.862, "stop": 188.682, "duration": 5.82}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, but you don't have to pay the person too much, he just has to write a letter saying give me these documents, right?", "start": 188.682, "stop": 192.736, "duration": 4.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--He would still have to hire someone, and that would be an increased cost.", "start": 192.736, "stop": 196.355, "duration": 3.62}, {"text": "And--", "start": 196.355, "stop": 196.922, "duration": 0.57}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, an increased cost of -- I don't know how much -- 100 bucks, right?", "start": 196.922, "stop": 201.676, "duration": 4.75}, {"text": "Go -- write a letter, say you want these documents, and when they come to your house, give them to me.", "start": 201.676, "stop": 206.644, "duration": 4.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yeah.", "start": 206.644, "stop": 207.18, "duration": 0.54}, {"text": "For the large data companies, you know, they will hire someone other than him to perform this service.", "start": 207.18, "stop": 212.983, "duration": 5.8}, {"text": "They will -- if you're talking about routine requests.", "start": 212.983, "stop": 216.268, "duration": 3.28}, {"text": "But even -- you know, even for them, if you're talking about a -- a request that isn't routine, if he has to do something further to enforce the rights, he's going to have to do that in his own name or the data company will have to hire someone other than him, someone based in Virginia, to do that for them.", "start": 216.268, "stop": 231.611, "duration": 15.34}, {"text": "And then he will lose that business.", "start": 231.611, "stop": 233.397, "duration": 1.79}, {"text": "So the lower you go down in the food chain of the data industry, the bigger the effect of Virginia's policy.", "start": 233.397, "stop": 238.765, "duration": 5.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "How much -- how much of an impact in fact does it have on his business?", "start": 238.765, "stop": 243.853, "duration": 5.09}, {"text": "I mean, there are 47 States who will provide this information.", "start": 243.853, "stop": 247.121, "duration": 3.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, for him, in the Virginia market, it completely forecloses him from doing access -- business in the Virginia market.", "start": 247.121, "stop": 254.81, "duration": 7.69}, {"text": "And if other States were to have policies like this, he wouldn't be able to do business in those States as well.", "start": 254.81, "stop": 259.862, "duration": 5.05}, {"text": "So if -- if the focus is on him and his business in Virginia, it completely cuts him off.", "start": 259.862, "stop": 266.284, "duration": 6.42}, {"text": "If the focus is on -- on what the effect is in the aggregate on the market as a whole, because most public records requests are commercial requests, it's going to have an effect on most commercial requesters who are out of State.", "start": 266.284, "stop": 280.426, "duration": 14.14}, {"text": "And--", "start": 280.426, "stop": 280.878, "duration": 0.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Gupta, I -- I understand that the -- the reasoning of Virginia in not allowing out of State people to -- to get these FOIA requests is the following: That the purpose of these -- these laws -- and I remember it when the first ones were enacted -- government in the sunshine.", "start": 280.878, "stop": 301.624, "duration": 20.75}, {"text": "The purpose of it was not to enable people to get information per se, it was to enable people to see how their government is working, so that they could attend to any malfeasance that is occurring in the process of government.", "start": 301.624, "stop": 318.151, "duration": 16.53}, {"text": "It seems to me entirely in accord with that purpose of these laws to say it's only Virginia citizens who -- who are concerned about the functioning of Virginia government, and ought to be able to get whatever records Virginia agencies have.", "start": 318.151, "stop": 332.41, "duration": 14.26}, {"text": "What's -- what's wrong with that reasoning?", "start": 332.41, "stop": 334.012, "duration": 1.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--A few responses, Justice Scalia.", "start": 334.012, "stop": 336.145, "duration": 2.13}, {"text": "First, transparency was one purpose, but as I said, these laws also carried forward the much more longstanding rights to access based on personal interests and property interests.", "start": 336.145, "stop": 346.153, "duration": 10.01}, {"text": "Also, even at the time that these laws were enacted--", "start": 346.153, "stop": 348.855, "duration": 2.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "But -- but you don't need any personal or property interest under these laws.", "start": 348.855, "stop": 352.824, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "You can just -- out of curiosity, if you -- if you were a Virginian at least in Virginia, even though you have no interest in the matter at all, you can ask the agency for records about this or that.", "start": 352.824, "stop": 363.365, "duration": 10.54}, {"text": "It -- it can't be based on -- on the traditional property interest.", "start": 363.365, "stop": 367.15, "duration": 3.78}, {"text": "It's based on the ability of the citizens of the State to find out what the -- what the government of the State is up to.", "start": 367.15, "stop": 374.387, "duration": 7.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Even -- even at the time that these laws were enacted in the -- in the '60s, it was well-understood that they were going to have a big commercial impact.", "start": 374.387, "stop": 382.426, "duration": 8.04}, {"text": "The property records industry was in full swing by the end of the late 19th Century.", "start": 382.426, "stop": 386.897, "duration": 4.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the point is that FOIA is tied to, as Justice Scalia said, the citizens should know what their government is doing.", "start": 386.897, "stop": 394.301, "duration": 7.4}, {"text": "And you don't have to give any reason at all, if you were a part of that political community.", "start": 394.301, "stop": 400.121, "duration": 5.82}, {"text": "Now, Virginia doesn't allow people from out of State to vote.", "start": 400.121, "stop": 404.423, "duration": 4.3}, {"text": "They're not part of Virginia's political community.", "start": 404.423, "stop": 407.292, "duration": 2.87}, {"text": "So why isn't this -- if you're not part of the political community, then you don't fall under FOIA, which is a peculiar statute, in that everybody who is covered by it can get whatever they want, and they don't have to give any reason for it.", "start": 407.292, "stop": 424.82, "duration": 17.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 424.82, "stop": 425.272, "duration": 0.45}, {"text": "Well, elections just simply don't work if you -- if you allow noncitizens to participate in elections, or if you can't wall off the State in that respect.", "start": 425.272, "stop": 433.859, "duration": 8.59}, {"text": "But what the State can't say is simply because one purpose of this law is that we want to constitute ourselves as a political community, that we can exclude activities that have a big commercial effect.", "start": 433.859, "stop": 444.734, "duration": 10.88}, {"text": "And, you know, when we're looking under the Dormant Commerce Clause or under the Privileges and Immunities Clause, this Court's cases have said repeatedly you don't look to uncover the original legislative purpose, you look to whether there is discrimination, which there is here on its face, and you look to whether there is a discriminatory effect.", "start": 444.734, "stop": 461.111, "duration": 16.38}, {"text": "One example of how this policy is actually being--", "start": 461.111, "stop": 464.747, "duration": 3.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "And is the only thing that's necessary -- excuse me -- is the only thing that's necessary that the law affect a few people commercially?", "start": 464.747, "stop": 471.817, "duration": 7.07}, {"text": "I mean, how much -- how many of the requesters have to be engaged in some kind of commercial activity in order for your arguments to work?", "start": 471.817, "stop": 480.823, "duration": 9.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, what this Court has said is that there is no de minimis exception if there's discrimination against commerce, but here, what's going on is anything but de minimis.", "start": 480.823, "stop": 489.279, "duration": 8.46}, {"text": "Virginia does not deny that the -- the vast majority of the requesters are commercial requesters, the vast majority of out of State requesters are commercial requesters.", "start": 489.279, "stop": 497.718, "duration": 8.44}, {"text": "Their -- the amicus brief supporting their side, the Local Government Attorneys of Virginia amicus brief at page 30 explains the way this policy is being implemented, is that noncommercial requests are typically honored, but out of State requests by data miners are being categorically denied under the policy.", "start": 497.718, "stop": 518.282, "duration": 20.56}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "But this is not -- this is not a regulation of commerce.", "start": 518.282, "stop": 521.484, "duration": 3.2}, {"text": "It's a State practice that may have an incidental effect on commerce, and the incidental effect may be disproportionate, depending upon whether you're State or local, but it's not a regulation of commerce.", "start": 521.484, "stop": 533.458, "duration": 11.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that's -- that was the Fourth Circuit's theory and I think incidental can mean a few different things, and I think in -- in their opinion, it -- it does mean at least three different things.", "start": 533.458, "stop": 542.397, "duration": 8.94}, {"text": "So maybe it would be helpful if I try to unpack that.", "start": 542.397, "stop": 544.682, "duration": 2.28}, {"text": "If it means incidental in terms of the effect on my client's business -- I think, as I've explained, it's anything but incidental; it completely forecloses him from the market.", "start": 544.682, "stop": 554.538, "duration": 9.86}, {"text": "If it means incidental in terms of the -- the aggregate effect of this statute, again, it's not incidental because the vast majority of -- of affected parties under this policy are out-of-state commercial requesters, particularly data companies.", "start": 554.538, "stop": 569.464, "duration": 14.93}, {"text": "And, you know, if it means incidental compared to the purpose of the statute, as I've said, transparency was one purpose of the modern FOIA laws, but they also subsumed and sit on top of all of the longstanding rights of public access that have been around since the -- the first settlements in the United States -- or before the United States, when in order to have a functioning property system, we recognized that you've got to have records of who owns what and -- and those records have to be made available to anyone in order to exercise property rights.", "start": 569.464, "stop": 600.65, "duration": 31.19}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What if the State of Virginia says, as a policy, we want to help Virginia businesses and so we're going to open a business training, best practices institute where you're going to learn how to be a better business person, but the only people who can come in are -- are Virginia businesses.", "start": 600.65, "stop": 617.128, "duration": 16.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 617.128, "stop": 617.544, "duration": 0.42}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Under your theory, because that will have an effect, an incidental effect on commerce in a way that's discriminatory, is -- is that unconstitutional?", "start": 617.544, "stop": 626.384, "duration": 8.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't think so.", "start": 626.384, "stop": 627.367, "duration": 0.98}, {"text": "And there are a couple of distinctions.", "start": 627.367, "stop": 628.836, "duration": 1.47}, {"text": "First, that's not something that the State exclusively is able to provide.", "start": 628.836, "stop": 634.656, "duration": 5.82}, {"text": "It's not like the courthouse or the public archives across the street or the road that runs between them that only the -- the State is able to provide.", "start": 634.656, "stop": 643.512, "duration": 8.86}, {"text": "Anyone can provide a business training institute, so the State is just one player among many.", "start": 643.512, "stop": 648.648, "duration": 5.14}, {"text": "Also--", "start": 648.648, "stop": 649.333, "duration": 0.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that -- that just goes to the extent of the impact, not -- not on the principle.", "start": 649.333, "stop": 655.237, "duration": 5.9}, {"text": "And you say extent doesn't matter.", "start": 655.237, "stop": 657.57, "duration": 2.33}, {"text": "You say there's no such thing as a de minimis exception.", "start": 657.57, "stop": 660.105, "duration": 2.53}, {"text": "So that -- that explanation doesn't -- doesn't seem to me to hold water.", "start": 660.105, "stop": 666.009, "duration": 5.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, maybe I didn't explain it very well.", "start": 666.009, "stop": 667.294, "duration": 1.28}, {"text": "To be clear, I think it's more than just a difference in degree; it's a difference in kind.", "start": 667.294, "stop": 670.663, "duration": 3.37}, {"text": "These are fundamentally different when -- when you're talking about running the courthouse or running the public archives, nobody else can do that.", "start": 670.663, "stop": 677.667, "duration": 7}, {"text": "Nobody else can collect -- you know, make tax assessments, collect those records and keep the official public archive of those things.", "start": 677.667, "stop": 685.506, "duration": 7.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "So what?", "start": 685.506, "stop": 686.589, "duration": 1.08}, {"text": "Except to the extent that that bears upon how much of an imposition this is upon interstate commerce.", "start": 686.589, "stop": 695.612, "duration": 9.02}, {"text": "It seems to me that's the only relevance of that point.", "start": 695.612, "stop": 697.647, "duration": 2.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well--", "start": 697.647, "stop": 698.547, "duration": 0.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "And -- and you dismiss that relevance.", "start": 698.547, "stop": 699.864, "duration": 1.32}, {"text": "You say it doesn't matter how extensive the impact is on -- on interstate commerce.", "start": 699.864, "stop": 704.484, "duration": 4.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, to the extent that you -- you think it does matter, I mean, that -- that distinction doesn't matter in this case because the impact is -- is great.", "start": 704.484, "stop": 713.339, "duration": 8.86}, {"text": "The principal impact is an impact on out-of-state commerce.", "start": 713.339, "stop": 716.958, "duration": 3.62}, {"text": "But let me--", "start": 716.958, "stop": 718.643, "duration": 1.69}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that -- when you're talking about impact, is that a Pike analysis?", "start": 718.643, "stop": 724.297, "duration": 5.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--No.", "start": 724.297, "stop": 725.281, "duration": 0.98}, {"text": "I think this -- if you were in -- in the dormant Commerce Clause, this would be the per se rule of invalidity.", "start": 725.281, "stop": 730.868, "duration": 5.59}, {"text": "You have facial discrimination.", "start": 730.868, "stop": 732.085, "duration": 1.22}, {"text": "The -- the--", "start": 732.085, "stop": 733.42, "duration": 1.33}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I thought if it was facial discrimination, you're not concerned about impact.", "start": 733.42, "stop": 736.539, "duration": 3.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's right.", "start": 736.539, "stop": 737.439, "duration": 0.9}, {"text": "That's right.", "start": 737.439, "stop": 737.755, "duration": 0.32}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I thought a question of talking about the effects on interstate commerce, that's the, you know, the Pike analysis.", "start": 737.755, "stop": 743.509, "duration": 5.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 743.509, "stop": 743.959, "duration": 0.45}, {"text": "What this Court has said is that -- that the first -- sort of first-tier scrutiny, the per se rule is -- is for cases where there's discrimination on its face or discrimination in effect.", "start": 743.959, "stop": 754.416, "duration": 10.46}, {"text": "And then you've got this other category for the -- the Pike analysis where the State regulates evenhandedly.", "start": 754.416, "stop": 760.637, "duration": 6.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "What's your closest case in support of the proposition that this is impermissible as a discrimination against interstate commerce?", "start": 760.637, "stop": 768.41, "duration": 7.77}, {"text": "What's your best case?", "start": 768.41, "stop": 769.326, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "When you say “ this ”, you mean the -- that public records access is commerce?", "start": 769.326, "stop": 775.747, "duration": 6.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "If -- if you -- you are arguing, as one of your arguments here, that this is discriminatory as to -- as to interstate commerce, as I understand your argument, what is the best case you have to support your position?", "start": 775.747, "stop": 788.121, "duration": 12.37}, {"text": "What's the closest case?", "start": 788.121, "stop": 789.239, "duration": 1.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think if you're -- if you're -- if the question is about whether or not records access is commerce, there's Reno v. Condon this Court's unanimous--", "start": 789.239, "stop": 797.679, "duration": 8.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, my question is what's the best case you have for your argument?", "start": 797.679, "stop": 800.279, "duration": 2.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, I think, you know, this Court's unanimous decision in Reno v. Condon held that because people buy public records and sell them in interstate commerce, that's indisputably interstate commerce.", "start": 800.279, "stop": 811.92, "duration": 11.64}, {"text": "So we--", "start": 811.92, "stop": 813.189, "duration": 1.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that wasn't a discrimination.", "start": 813.189, "stop": 814.589, "duration": 1.4}, {"text": "That wasn't a--", "start": 814.589, "stop": 815.322, "duration": 0.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's right.", "start": 815.322, "stop": 815.641, "duration": 0.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's just -- that goes to the question whether or not this is commerce.", "start": 815.641, "stop": 818.426, "duration": 2.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "That -- that's right.", "start": 818.426, "stop": 819.376, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "What is your best case to show that this is discriminatory in violation of our precedence?", "start": 819.376, "stop": 825.08, "duration": 5.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Virginia doesn't deny that there's discrimination on its face, so I take your question to be asking, you know, what about the commerce aspect.", "start": 825.08, "stop": 832.816, "duration": 7.74}, {"text": "And in Reno v. Condon--", "start": 832.816, "stop": 834.352, "duration": 1.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "If I have to write the opinion, what case do I put down?", "start": 834.352, "stop": 836.47, "duration": 2.12}, {"text": "I'm waiting.", "start": 836.47, "stop": 836.97, "duration": 0.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yeah, I mean, you -- okay.", "start": 836.97, "stop": 837.937, "duration": 0.97}, {"text": "So you can also look to Camps Newfound, which, I think, you know, was much, more attenuated to commerce.", "start": 837.937, "stop": 843.874, "duration": 5.94}, {"text": "There you had a generally applicable law, a property tax law--", "start": 843.874, "stop": 848.278, "duration": 4.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "If I only have time to read one case--", "start": 848.278, "stop": 849.895, "duration": 1.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yeah.", "start": 849.895, "stop": 850.295, "duration": 0.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "--or possibly two, which would you like me to read?", "start": 850.295, "stop": 853.33, "duration": 3.04}, {"text": "I think that's basically the question.", "start": 853.33, "stop": 855.449, "duration": 2.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yeah.", "start": 855.449, "stop": 855.899, "duration": 0.45}, {"text": "I mean, you know, look.", "start": 855.899, "stop": 857.051, "duration": 1.15}, {"text": "There's no case that's -- that's entirely on all fours, but--", "start": 857.051, "stop": 859.801, "duration": 2.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Okay.", "start": 859.801, "stop": 860.086, "duration": 0.28}, {"text": "But I assume you don't want me--", "start": 860.086, "stop": 860.503, "duration": 0.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's why you're here.", "start": 860.503, "stop": 861.386, "duration": 0.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--So right.", "start": 861.386, "stop": 862.169, "duration": 0.78}, {"text": "So -- so -- okay.", "start": 862.169, "stop": 863.371, "duration": 1.2}, {"text": "So the Camps Newfound case is -- is a case where you had a generally applicable law.", "start": 863.371, "stop": 869.459, "duration": 6.09}, {"text": "It was a property tax law.", "start": 869.459, "stop": 870.742, "duration": 1.28}, {"text": "It exempted, you know, charities that served primarily in-state residents.", "start": 870.742, "stop": 876.846, "duration": 6.1}, {"text": "It was -- there is no evidence that the State of Maine intended that to be a, you know, a discrimination against commerce, and obviously swept more broadly and affected both commerce and non-commerce.", "start": 876.846, "stop": 887.57, "duration": 10.72}, {"text": "But this Court said that, you know, you had facial discrimination against commerce because there were people operating these summer camps and they were treated differently--", "start": 887.57, "stop": 896.259, "duration": 8.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Look at those.", "start": 896.259, "stop": 897.442, "duration": 1.18}, {"text": "But I think the Commerce Clause basically has as its objective, insofar as it's dormant, to prevent a legislature or decisionmaker within its State discriminating in favor of their own state producers.", "start": 897.442, "stop": 911.369, "duration": 13.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Right.", "start": 911.369, "stop": 911.852, "duration": 0.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, it's pretty hard for me to put this case into that mold.", "start": 911.852, "stop": 915.138, "duration": 3.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I mean, one -- you know, one piece of evidence, Justice Breyer, is the media exception to the Virginia statute.", "start": 915.138, "stop": 921.307, "duration": 6.17}, {"text": "It -- this -- this makes it clear that Virginia was aware that people who were requesting information for commercial purposes were going to use this statute and they exempted the press--", "start": 921.307, "stop": 931.932, "duration": 10.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Just Virginia media, though, isn't it?", "start": 931.932, "stop": 933.199, "duration": 1.27}, {"text": "Isn't it only media that--", "start": 933.199, "stop": 934.717, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's right, Justice Scalia.", "start": 934.717, "stop": 936.753, "duration": 2.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "--exists or is broadcast into Virginia?", "start": 936.753, "stop": 938.886, "duration": 2.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 938.886, "stop": 939.955, "duration": 1.07}, {"text": "So it's -- it's--", "start": 939.955, "stop": 940.538, "duration": 0.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "So that's consistent with their purpose that this statute is meant to assure good, honest government in Virginia.", "start": 940.538, "stop": 948.125, "duration": 7.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, if this is a statute, it's a pretty unusual statute that discriminates among newspapers.", "start": 948.125, "stop": 952.596, "duration": 4.47}, {"text": "So it says--", "start": 952.596, "stop": 953.013, "duration": 0.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "If it does what the -- I had exactly the same question for both parts of your argument, that, what it's their -- am I right in thinking that anyone can get any information -- anyone in any State can get any information that pertains to him or her?", "start": 953.013, "stop": 969.89, "duration": 16.88}, {"text": "Is that right or not?", "start": 969.89, "stop": 973.026, "duration": 3.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--There is a separate Virginia--", "start": 973.026, "stop": 974.542, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that right or not?", "start": 974.542, "stop": 975.294, "duration": 0.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes.", "start": 975.294, "stop": 975.928, "duration": 0.63}, {"text": "There is a separate Virginia statute that allows this.", "start": 975.928, "stop": 977.794, "duration": 1.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Okay.", "start": 977.794, "stop": 978.496, "duration": 0.7}, {"text": "That's what I wanted to know, whether it's separate or not.", "start": 978.496, "stop": 979.013, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 979.013, "stop": 979.546, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Anyone from Alaska to Hawaii can get any information that pertains to him or her.", "start": 979.546, "stop": 984.567, "duration": 5.02}, {"text": "Second, that this has nothing to do with judicial records.", "start": 984.567, "stop": 988.019, "duration": 3.45}, {"text": "There is a different statute that makes judicial records public.", "start": 988.019, "stop": 991.638, "duration": 3.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 991.638, "stop": 992.554, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Okay.", "start": 992.554, "stop": 993.09, "duration": 0.54}, {"text": "So we're now talking about the class of information other than the two classes I've mentioned.", "start": 993.09, "stop": 998.292, "duration": 5.2}, {"text": "And I then ended up, and I'd like you to add something to this, if you can, that really this is about, since getting information involves usually a benefit to the recipient, but sometimes harm to the person the information is about, that willing to run that harm and risk of harm is the interest in State good government, okay?", "start": 998.292, "stop": 1023.525, "duration": 25.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Uh-huh.", "start": 1023.525, "stop": 1024.009, "duration": 0.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, if that's the interest, that's an interest that probably a State has the right, just as it has the right to say other people can't vote in State elections.", "start": 1024.009, "stop": 1034.417, "duration": 10.41}, {"text": "If that's the interest, then I guess it could take reasonable measures related to that interest.", "start": 1034.417, "stop": 1040.571, "duration": 6.15}, {"text": "All right.", "start": 1040.571, "stop": 1041.221, "duration": 0.65}, {"text": "Now, that is the -- the argument or the position that I would appreciate your addressing.", "start": 1041.221, "stop": 1047.241, "duration": 6.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Sure.", "start": 1047.241, "stop": 1047.791, "duration": 0.55}, {"text": "You know, that -- we don't deny that that's an interest that the State has, but then you have to see whether the -- the interest is reasonably furthered by the statute.", "start": 1047.791, "stop": 1056.763, "duration": 8.97}, {"text": "And here you have a resource that is not finite and the statute allows the State to recoup its expenses.", "start": 1056.763, "stop": 1063.567, "duration": 6.8}, {"text": "So nothing is lost to Virginians.", "start": 1063.567, "stop": 1066.186, "duration": 2.62}, {"text": "There isn't any loss in transparency to Virginians by extending access to out-of-state data companies.", "start": 1066.186, "stop": 1072.523, "duration": 6.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "But if it costs for Virginia -- Virginia has to take care of its own, and if it has to service FOIA requests from all over, it's going to cost the State.", "start": 1072.523, "stop": 1085.35, "duration": 12.83}, {"text": "It's going to have to hire people to do this.", "start": 1085.35, "stop": 1087.885, "duration": 2.54}, {"text": "They're going to have to spend many hours going through these records.", "start": 1087.885, "stop": 1091.337, "duration": 3.45}, {"text": "So the State doesn't -- it wants to conserve its resources for its own people.", "start": 1091.337, "stop": 1098.49, "duration": 7.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "But -- but there's no loss in resources, Justice Ginsburg, because the statute allows Virginia to fully recoup any administrative expenses.", "start": 1098.49, "stop": 1106.513, "duration": 8.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Counsel, I'm having--", "start": 1106.513, "stop": 1107.979, "duration": 1.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "But they -- but they just don't want out -- they -- they don't want outlanders mucking around in -- in Virginia government.", "start": 1107.979, "stop": 1113.35, "duration": 5.37}, {"text": "It's perfectly okay for good old Virginians to do that, but they don't want outlanders to do it.", "start": 1113.35, "stop": 1119.837, "duration": 6.49}, {"text": "Why -- why is that unreasonable?", "start": 1119.837, "stop": 1121.373, "duration": 1.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yeah.", "start": 1121.373, "stop": 1122.523, "duration": 1.15}, {"text": "That -- that is certainly their interest.", "start": 1122.523, "stop": 1124.391, "duration": 1.87}, {"text": "But you've got to see whether the policy serves -- serves, you know, the interest, and -- and this is a statute that is supposed to promote transparency.", "start": 1124.391, "stop": 1132.847, "duration": 8.46}, {"text": "It actually makes less transparent.", "start": 1132.847, "stop": 1134.865, "duration": 2.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Counsel, I'm -- I -- there is underlying your argument a sort of fundamental belief that you are entitled to relief -- pardon the alliteration simply because the statute discriminates between citizens and noncitizens.", "start": 1134.865, "stop": 1151.725, "duration": 16.86}, {"text": "Is that your position?", "start": 1151.725, "stop": 1153.244, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, not at all.", "start": 1153.244, "stop": 1154.327, "duration": 1.08}, {"text": "I mean--", "start": 1154.327, "stop": 1154.844, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "So if it's not, what are the two rights that you -- or what rights are it that you're claiming have been violated?", "start": 1154.844, "stop": 1162.933, "duration": 8.09}, {"text": "You say privileges and immunities.", "start": 1162.933, "stop": 1164.735, "duration": 1.8}, {"text": "What's the privilege or immunity?", "start": 1164.735, "stop": 1166.702, "duration": 1.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It's the privilege or immunity of pursuing a common calling across State borders.", "start": 1166.702, "stop": 1171.289, "duration": 4.59}, {"text": "So there's no dispute here that Mr. Hurlbert's common calling is -- is gathering data.", "start": 1171.289, "stop": 1176.609, "duration": 5.32}, {"text": "In fact, those are the principal users of public records laws.", "start": 1176.609, "stop": 1181.811, "duration": 5.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "So is this an as-applied challenge to the--", "start": 1181.811, "stop": 1185.013, "duration": 3.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 1185.013, "stop": 1185.363, "duration": 0.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--All right.", "start": 1185.363, "stop": 1185.715, "duration": 0.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 1185.715, "stop": 1186.231, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "So this is an as-applied challenge.", "start": 1186.231, "stop": 1187.365, "duration": 1.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1187.365, "stop": 1188.115, "duration": 0.75}, {"text": "So -- so it's an as-applied challenge with respect to Mr. Hurlbert's common calling.", "start": 1188.115, "stop": 1191.952, "duration": 3.84}, {"text": "There's no -- there's no dispute that that is his common calling and that this law has the effect of completely cutting him off from pursuing his common calling in the Virginia market and that 47 other States--", "start": 1191.952, "stop": 1203.859, "duration": 11.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Then you would be doing something very strange with this statute, because you would be saying Hurlbert has a right to this because it's his business.", "start": 1203.859, "stop": 1212.198, "duration": 8.34}, {"text": "But the statute, the character of this statute is it doesn't matter what you want the information for.", "start": 1212.198, "stop": 1219.268, "duration": 7.07}, {"text": "But you're saying the out-of -- the in-Stater, it doesn't matter.", "start": 1219.268, "stop": 1223.47, "duration": 4.2}, {"text": "Out-of-Stater, is it your argument that if this out-of-Stater has a good reason for getting this and it's related to the out-of-State's business, so you -- you're changing the character of a FOIA statute which is it doesn't matter what you want it for.", "start": 1223.47, "stop": 1239.515, "duration": 16.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Right.", "start": 1239.515, "stop": 1240.181, "duration": 0.67}, {"text": "I mean, you would, you know, we would -- we would ask that you rule that the statute is unconstitutional as applied to him and then Virginia would have the choice if it has a to the statute--", "start": 1240.181, "stop": 1248.704, "duration": 8.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I'm having a problem, and then I think it's Justice Ginsburg's problem, which is absent the statute, he can't demand that Virginia provide him with this information because that's how he wants to work, correct?", "start": 1248.704, "stop": 1261.612, "duration": 12.91}, {"text": "So what's the added value that gives him a right to demand it merely because a statute exists?", "start": 1261.612, "stop": 1268.766, "duration": 7.15}, {"text": "He doesn't have a right to the information.", "start": 1268.766, "stop": 1271.134, "duration": 2.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, he's -- all he's asking for is information that's available in the public archives on equal terms with Virginians.", "start": 1271.134, "stop": 1278.638, "duration": 7.5}, {"text": "In the same way that -- that someone who--", "start": 1278.638, "stop": 1281.507, "duration": 2.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "He -- he has a very reasonable request in my view, but the question isn't the reasonableness of his request.", "start": 1281.507, "stop": 1288.345, "duration": 6.84}, {"text": "The question's, you know, whether they can do it.", "start": 1288.345, "stop": 1290.779, "duration": 2.43}, {"text": "And the -- the way -- the work -- the thing that's bothering me on the work part is this: It seems that the work is sort of tailored to the statute.", "start": 1290.779, "stop": 1301.57, "duration": 10.79}, {"text": "It's in this way.", "start": 1301.57, "stop": 1303.189, "duration": 1.62}, {"text": "I -- I have a job and my job is to study election processes.", "start": 1303.189, "stop": 1308.557, "duration": 5.37}, {"text": "And I write reports and I find amazing things about differences among States.", "start": 1308.557, "stop": 1313.461, "duration": 4.9}, {"text": "They're truly amazing.", "start": 1313.461, "stop": 1314.83, "duration": 1.37}, {"text": "And I say, you know, it would help me a lot if I was actually a voter in each of these states.", "start": 1314.83, "stop": 1320.734, "duration": 5.9}, {"text": "That would help my job.", "start": 1320.734, "stop": 1322.817, "duration": 2.08}, {"text": "It would lend authenticity and I could learn things that I probably couldn't learn otherwise.", "start": 1322.817, "stop": 1327.404, "duration": 4.59}, {"text": "Now, does that add anything to the argument?", "start": 1327.404, "stop": 1330.506, "duration": 3.1}, {"text": "I mean, I don't think so, but it sounds a little bit like you're making that kind of argument--", "start": 1330.506, "stop": 1336.66, "duration": 6.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--No.", "start": 1336.66, "stop": 1337.31, "duration": 0.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "--and -- and they either do have the right or they don't.", "start": 1337.31, "stop": 1339.778, "duration": 2.47}, {"text": "And I don't know that it helps that I -- that I say, well, I really want it for my work.", "start": 1339.778, "stop": 1345.266, "duration": 5.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 1345.266, "stop": 1345.799, "duration": 0.53}, {"text": "But this is -- this is a profession that has existed since the founding era.", "start": 1345.799, "stop": 1349.718, "duration": 3.92}, {"text": "I mean, we've, you know, we've cited cases in our opening brief of -- of people hiring professionals to search the records for them before engaging in property transactions.", "start": 1349.718, "stop": 1358.907, "duration": 9.19}, {"text": "By the late 19th Century, you had an enormous industry that was designed to do this.", "start": 1358.907, "stop": 1363.394, "duration": 4.49}, {"text": "So this isn't -- Mr. Hurlbert isn't some -- someone who's making up some profession.", "start": 1363.394, "stop": 1367.512, "duration": 4.12}, {"text": "He's part of a very large industry that has done this for a very long time.", "start": 1367.512, "stop": 1370.916, "duration": 3.4}, {"text": "And that industry, yes, like lawyers depend on courthouses or truckers depend on roads, his industry depends on access to the public archives.", "start": 1370.916, "stop": 1380.522, "duration": 9.61}, {"text": "And, you know, it's true that -- that now you have these modern public records laws, but I -- I think Virginia's argument would be the same if you were just talking about can -- can they bar the doors to the archives building?", "start": 1380.522, "stop": 1391.93, "duration": 11.41}, {"text": "Can they bar the doors to the property records?", "start": 1391.93, "stop": 1394.449, "duration": 2.52}, {"text": "So there's no -- I don't see any distinction in kind--", "start": 1394.449, "stop": 1396.449, "duration": 2}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is this -- is this your Privileges and Immunities argument or your dormant Commerce Clause argument?", "start": 1396.449, "stop": 1400.603, "duration": 4.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--You know, I think the logic of both arguments are similar, but I think it most clearly is illustrated in the Privileges and Immunities context where--", "start": 1400.603, "stop": 1408.006, "duration": 7.4}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So then it's not enough that this is a big deal to your client.", "start": 1408.006, "stop": 1410.874, "duration": 2.87}, {"text": "It has to be something that is essential to hold the country together as a national unit.", "start": 1410.874, "stop": 1416.195, "duration": 5.32}, {"text": "And it seems to me it's a bit of a stretch to say somebody gathering records about commercial -- under FOIA fits that description.", "start": 1416.195, "stop": 1427.253, "duration": 11.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I don't think it's a stretch at all, Justice -- Chief Justice.", "start": 1427.253, "stop": 1430.288, "duration": 3.04}, {"text": "The -- the aggregators of records make possible mortgage origination, credit reporting, insurance adjustment.", "start": 1430.288, "stop": 1438.728, "duration": 8.44}, {"text": "The -- the economy -- and you have an amicus brief--", "start": 1438.728, "stop": 1441.294, "duration": 2.57}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, but see, they're just to get into those.", "start": 1441.294, "stop": 1442.43, "duration": 1.14}, {"text": "Again, I think a lot of those examples you -- you do have access under other statutes.", "start": 1442.43, "stop": 1448.583, "duration": 6.15}, {"text": "You're talking about mortgage rules and all that.", "start": 1448.583, "stop": 1452.035, "duration": 3.45}, {"text": "Aren't those all--", "start": 1452.035, "stop": 1452.785, "duration": 0.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--No, no.", "start": 1452.785, "stop": 1452.985, "duration": 0.2}, {"text": "Not to this kind of information.", "start": 1452.985, "stop": 1453.385, "duration": 0.4}, {"text": "The -- the information that Mr. Hurlbert is gathering, tax assessment information, is essential to -- to mortgage origination and credit reporting.", "start": 1453.385, "stop": 1460.891, "duration": 7.51}, {"text": "The people who hire him are large data companies, and the -- the data industry brief explains the uses of this information.", "start": 1460.891, "stop": 1466.961, "duration": 6.07}, {"text": "That -- that information is essential to these activities.", "start": 1466.961, "stop": 1469.83, "duration": 2.87}, {"text": "And Virginia, virtually alone among the States, is -- is erecting this barrier to access that market, and reserving the right to access that market to only people who live in the State.", "start": 1469.83, "stop": 1482.054, "duration": 12.22}, {"text": "And -- and, you know, this would be no different if it were just talking about the archives that -- that include all the information that the -- yes, it's true that Virginia has exempted of the title itself, but I don't see that the logic of their position allows them to make that distinction.", "start": 1482.054, "stop": 1498.997, "duration": 16.94}, {"text": "I mean, that's just a feature of their -- of their statute.", "start": 1498.997, "stop": 1501.699, "duration": 2.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm still trying to tease out what your claim is.", "start": 1501.699, "stop": 1505.836, "duration": 4.14}, {"text": "Let's suppose Virginia passes a statute that says: We'll let nonresidents have access, but they have to pay all the costs.", "start": 1505.836, "stop": 1515.275, "duration": 9.44}, {"text": "Nonresidents don't.", "start": 1515.275, "stop": 1517.06, "duration": 1.78}, {"text": "Would that satisfy you as valid?", "start": 1517.06, "stop": 1521.445, "duration": 4.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that would be a closer question, but I think that presents some problems as well.", "start": 1521.445, "stop": 1525.833, "duration": 4.39}, {"text": "I mean, so in your hypothetical it's free to the citizens of the State, but they're just passing the cost on to out-of-Staters.", "start": 1525.833, "stop": 1531.903, "duration": 6.07}, {"text": "And, you know, this -- this Court in cases like Toomer and Mullaney have said that at least, you know, where the State can show that the nonresidents pose some unique evil, that the -- the State is entitled to pass the costs on.", "start": 1531.903, "stop": 1544.395, "duration": 12.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why isn't it just -- you just being costs them more?", "start": 1544.395, "stop": 1546.58, "duration": 2.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 1546.58, "stop": 1547.03, "duration": 0.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "That was Justice Ginsburg's point, which is every time you've put in a request, you're costing them more money.", "start": 1547.03, "stop": 1553.817, "duration": 6.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 1553.817, "stop": 1554.133, "duration": 0.32}, {"text": "But -- but that would be discriminating against not as -- noncitizens solely because they're noncitizens.", "start": 1554.133, "stop": 1558.387, "duration": 4.25}, {"text": "So if there's some particular--", "start": 1558.387, "stop": 1559.654, "duration": 1.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, why?", "start": 1559.654, "stop": 1560.354, "duration": 0.7}, {"text": "You were costing them more.", "start": 1560.354, "stop": 1561.07, "duration": 0.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Right.", "start": 1561.07, "stop": 1561.672, "duration": 0.6}, {"text": "Well, that's -- that's precisely the rationale that -- that in Justice Kennedy's opinion for the Court in Barnard v. Thorstenn, this Court rejected.", "start": 1561.672, "stop": 1567.743, "duration": 6.07}, {"text": "This -- the Virgin Islands wanted to say if we open up our bar to people from all over the country, it's going to increase the administrative resources, and this Court said, no, that's not a good a enough reason.", "start": 1567.743, "stop": 1577.266, "duration": 9.52}, {"text": "That's just discriminating on the basis of citizenship.", "start": 1577.266, "stop": 1579.551, "duration": 2.28}, {"text": "But if, for example, the State could show that there was, you know, there were shipping costs that were uniquely posed by nonresidents and they wanted to assess a $5 shipping fee for all nonresidents, that might be permissible.", "start": 1579.551, "stop": 1592.109, "duration": 12.56}, {"text": "And if there are no further questions, I'd like to reserve my time.", "start": 1592.109, "stop": 1595.393, "duration": 3.28}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Thank you, counsel.", "start": 1595.393, "stop": 1595.977, "duration": 0.58}, {"text": "General Getchell?", "start": 1595.977, "stop": 1600.464, "duration": 4.49}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:", "start": 1600.464, "stop": 1604.249, "duration": 3.79}, {"text": "The--", "start": 1604.249, "stop": 1606.285, "duration": 2.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm not sure how you save administrative costs under this statute.", "start": 1606.285, "stop": 1612.772, "duration": 6.49}, {"text": "They could go to any Virginia resident, it's not illegal, and probably will, it'll cost them something more, but not you, and get the very same information.", "start": 1612.772, "stop": 1624.93, "duration": 12.16}, {"text": "So how do you justify this discrimination?", "start": 1624.93, "stop": 1628.382, "duration": 3.45}, {"text": "Because it's so easily -- the administrative cost is going to be imposed anyway.", "start": 1628.382, "stop": 1634.703, "duration": 6.32}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I would suggest that the purpose of the statute, which is political, not commercial, left the State with the position that it was going to subsidize with tax dollars this function because we can't recover our overhead; we can over -- only recover the actual cost.", "start": 1634.703, "stop": 1654.432, "duration": 19.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "So you want to give more businesses to Virginia citizens who will now charge out-of-State residents money to process their FOIA requests?", "start": 1654.432, "stop": 1662.872, "duration": 8.44}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, Your Honor.", "start": 1662.872, "stop": 1664.205, "duration": 1.33}, {"text": "I don't think anybody was thinking about businesses of any sort.", "start": 1664.205, "stop": 1667.609, "duration": 3.4}, {"text": "I think they were saying that we have a political hygiene statute.", "start": 1667.609, "stop": 1671.744, "duration": 4.13}, {"text": "They were very much the fad.", "start": 1671.744, "stop": 1673.078, "duration": 1.33}, {"text": "It happened in my lifetime, too.", "start": 1673.078, "stop": 1675.513, "duration": 2.43}, {"text": "I remember when they were adopted.", "start": 1675.513, "stop": 1677.047, "duration": 1.53}, {"text": "Nobody thought they were commercial in nature.", "start": 1677.047, "stop": 1679.583, "duration": 2.54}, {"text": "And I do want to -- want to repel the notion that there is even substantial discrimination in this case, because Mr. Hurlbert, in his admission that this is an as-applied challenge, has a difficulty with substantial equality of access, because it turns out that Mr. Hurlbert, in his reply brief, when he teed up the 1786 statute, which does give access -- did give access, he focused his argument on that statute.", "start": 1679.583, "stop": 1715.589, "duration": 36.01}, {"text": "And if you run that statute, you will find that between 1830 -- 1813 and 1840, that you did not have general access.", "start": 1715.589, "stop": 1727.33, "duration": 11.74}, {"text": "They went back to having to show a particular interest.", "start": 1727.33, "stop": 1730.266, "duration": 2.94}, {"text": "But that -- from 1840, '41 until today, through the codes of 1819 and -- and up until the present code, Section 17.1208, he has the right of access to tax assessment records.", "start": 1730.266, "stop": 1747.894, "duration": 17.63}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So if I understood your answer to Justice Sotomayor, the only reason you don't let out-of-staters get these records is because of the added overhead costs?", "start": 1747.894, "stop": 1757.333, "duration": 9.44}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, Your Honor.", "start": 1757.333, "stop": 1758.283, "duration": 0.95}, {"text": "It's just not part of the interests the State was trying to serve.", "start": 1758.283, "stop": 1762.487, "duration": 4.2}, {"text": "The State--", "start": 1762.487, "stop": 1763.437, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I know.", "start": 1763.437, "stop": 1763.837, "duration": 0.4}, {"text": "But -- but -- so why don't you do it anyways?", "start": 1763.837, "stop": 1767.789, "duration": 3.95}, {"text": "Just as I asked your friend, it doesn't seem like that big a deal.", "start": 1767.789, "stop": 1771.426, "duration": 3.64}, {"text": "It doesn't seem like that big a deal for you either.", "start": 1771.426, "stop": 1773.961, "duration": 2.54}, {"text": "If you can recoup overhead costs from people who request, and I'd assume you would be able to, why don't other people -- people from West Virginia may have interest in how Virginia government operates, too.", "start": 1773.961, "stop": 1786.603, "duration": 12.64}, {"text": "And -- and again, what cost is there to you other than overhead?", "start": 1786.603, "stop": 1793.94, "duration": 7.34}, {"text": "You don't want to keep how Virginia government operates quiet from outsiders when you let in -- its citizens get the access, do you?", "start": 1793.94, "stop": 1801.695, "duration": 7.75}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--The -- we are here to defend the decisions of the two lower courts that apply existing doctrine.", "start": 1801.695, "stop": 1811.901, "duration": 10.21}, {"text": "And under existing doctrine, only if we discover that this is a fundamental right do I have to justify--", "start": 1811.901, "stop": 1818.657, "duration": 6.76}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's under the Privileges -- Privileges and Immunities argument.", "start": 1818.657, "stop": 1822.209, "duration": 3.55}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's correct.", "start": 1822.209, "stop": 1822.759, "duration": 0.55}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Okay.", "start": 1822.759, "stop": 1823.226, "duration": 0.47}, {"text": "But what about the Dormant Commerce Clause?", "start": 1823.226, "stop": 1825.244, "duration": 2.02}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Under the Dormant Commerce Clause, we would first have to have a regulation of commerce that's discriminatory.", "start": 1825.244, "stop": 1831.132, "duration": 5.89}, {"text": "And I would say that a -- that this is a governmental function.", "start": 1831.132, "stop": 1835.35, "duration": 4.22}, {"text": "I would say that--", "start": 1835.35, "stop": 1835.952, "duration": 0.6}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, I know -- I understand your argument.", "start": 1835.952, "stop": 1837.552, "duration": 1.6}, {"text": "I'm just asking you why bother?", "start": 1837.552, "stop": 1840.253, "duration": 2.7}, {"text": "I mean, what -- what's the -- and that's certainly pertinent to some of the Commerce Clause analysis.", "start": 1840.253, "stop": 1846.824, "duration": 6.57}, {"text": "And I haven't heard anything other than the overhead costs.", "start": 1846.824, "stop": 1851.128, "duration": 4.3}, {"text": "And I think you can recoup that from the requesters.", "start": 1851.128, "stop": 1853.747, "duration": 2.62}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I cannot, Your Honor.", "start": 1853.747, "stop": 1855.03, "duration": 1.28}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why not?", "start": 1855.03, "stop": 1855.68, "duration": 0.65}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, the statute says I cannot recoup the cost of maintaining and generating the database, which is by definition overhead.", "start": 1855.68, "stop": 1866.988, "duration": 11.31}, {"text": "I cannot--", "start": 1866.988, "stop": 1867.605, "duration": 0.62}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, you've got to maintain and generate the database anyway for Virginia citizens who are going to ask for it.", "start": 1867.605, "stop": 1871.642, "duration": 4.04}, {"text": "This is not an added cost.", "start": 1871.642, "stop": 1873.159, "duration": 1.52}, {"text": "Other than -- it's an added cost if you have to hire an additional person to handle -- as far as I can tell, just these two people.", "start": 1873.159, "stop": 1880.147, "duration": 6.99}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It's an added burden, too.", "start": 1880.147, "stop": 1881.364, "duration": 1.22}, {"text": "It's not all--", "start": 1881.364, "stop": 1881.73, "duration": 0.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the Virginia citizens pay for that database, right?", "start": 1881.73, "stop": 1885.532, "duration": 3.8}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--They do.", "start": 1885.532, "stop": 1885.968, "duration": 0.44}, {"text": "This is a--", "start": 1885.968, "stop": 1886.468, "duration": 0.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "And the out-of-staters don't pay for the database.", "start": 1886.468, "stop": 1888.92, "duration": 2.45}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--This is a taxpayer subsidized system.", "start": 1888.92, "stop": 1890.92, "duration": 2}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "And besides, do -- do you -- is it the law that -- that the State of Virginia cannot do anything that's pointless?", "start": 1890.92, "stop": 1898.692, "duration": 7.77}, {"text": "Only the Federal Government can do stuff that's pointless?", "start": 1898.692, "stop": 1903.228, "duration": 4.54}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 1903.228, "stop": 1904.263, "duration": 1.03}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "The -- there is a burden -- there is a non-financial burden as well, because as one who is subject to FOIA requests, we have a finite number of officials and employees who have to address these things.", "start": 1904.263, "stop": 1918.689, "duration": 14.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "You keep making that argument.", "start": 1918.689, "stop": 1921.022, "duration": 2.33}, {"text": "But you don't stop residents for asking for the information from someone else.", "start": 1921.022, "stop": 1925.593, "duration": 4.57}, {"text": "I mean, that's one of the points of your law, which is, they can hire a Virginia resident to get it for them.", "start": 1925.593, "stop": 1932.747, "duration": 7.15}, {"text": "Most of the big people are doing that already.", "start": 1932.747, "stop": 1936.234, "duration": 3.49}, {"text": "So you're not saving any money if they can get the information simply by paying someone in Virginia to get it for them.", "start": 1936.234, "stop": 1943.888, "duration": 7.65}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "In -- in fact, the State of Virginia has made the policy decision to give this information to its citizens, and not to inquire behind it to see whether or not somebody's doing it for an out-of-Stater.", "start": 1943.888, "stop": 1958.898, "duration": 15.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or even for commercial purposes.", "start": 1958.898, "stop": 1961.616, "duration": 2.72}, {"text": "Don't you think if -- if those who created these government in the sunshine laws could have drafted them in such a way that inquiries for commercial purposes would not be allowed, but only those inquiries that are intended to look into the workings of State government and produce government in the sunshine, don't you think that they probably would have excluded commercial inquiries if they could?", "start": 1961.616, "stop": 1986.334, "duration": 24.72}, {"text": "But you can't tell which ones are commercial and which aren't.", "start": 1986.334, "stop": 1989.952, "duration": 3.62}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And we don't -- and we don't try.", "start": 1989.952, "stop": 1991.836, "duration": 1.88}, {"text": "We have a policy decision that we want to have a very simple system that allows our citizens to make inquiries without a demonstrated need or cause, because we want there to be sunshine.", "start": 1991.836, "stop": 2004.295, "duration": 12.46}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's no more complicated in the system if you let out-of-Staters have access, too.", "start": 2004.295, "stop": 2009.163, "duration": 4.87}, {"text": "You say we want a simple system.", "start": 2009.163, "stop": 2010.365, "duration": 1.2}, {"text": "It's going to be the same system whether you win or lose.", "start": 2010.365, "stop": 2012.901, "duration": 2.54}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "The thing that is of -- of great concern -- why do we care?", "start": 2012.901, "stop": 2018.186, "duration": 5.28}, {"text": "Why do we bother -- is the principle that when a government is providing a taxpayer-subsidized service of recent origin to its citizens, that it does not have to explain its choice either under the Privileges and Immunities Clause or under the Dormant Commerce Clause.", "start": 2018.186, "stop": 2037.933, "duration": 19.75}, {"text": "It is very important that we not find ourselves with lawsuits that say “ services ”.", "start": 2037.933, "stop": 2045.788, "duration": 7.86}, {"text": "Voluntary services are in fact things that now have to be justified under those two provisions of the Constitution.", "start": 2045.788, "stop": 2054.126, "duration": 8.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's where he comes in with his argument.", "start": 2054.126, "stop": 2055.994, "duration": 1.87}, {"text": "Because I -- I agree, you can -- you don't have -- let's say the most fabulous reason for doing this, but you have a reason.", "start": 2055.994, "stop": 2062.132, "duration": 6.14}, {"text": "And so the question is, does it have to be better than that?", "start": 2062.132, "stop": 2067.286, "duration": 5.15}, {"text": "And -- and they are saying yes.", "start": 2067.286, "stop": 2071.154, "duration": 3.87}, {"text": "And as I heard it, what I would characterize as a strong argument, which sort of first of all strikes me as a stronger argument, is that, look, if we go back into history, out of State real estate people could always get information about property -- let's say they had a client who wanted to buy it.", "start": 2071.154, "stop": 2091.115, "duration": 19.96}, {"text": "Now, you've protected that.", "start": 2091.115, "stop": 2092.417, "duration": 1.3}, {"text": "But in today's world, it's important that we get statistics about this, too, because our economy is national.", "start": 2092.417, "stop": 2101.423, "duration": 9.01}, {"text": "If we understand how States are taxing their real estate, we will know to what extent they increase the value, to what extent they increase the rate, to what extent they really get the money they are supposed to, to what extent they might get money or not get money in the future.", "start": 2101.423, "stop": 2118.283, "duration": 16.86}, {"text": "And all of those things are nationally important so people can put them together and make, better than we have done in the past, predictions about what is likely to happen to States, and hence, the national economy.", "start": 2118.283, "stop": 2130.275, "duration": 11.99}, {"text": "All right?", "start": 2130.275, "stop": 2131.108, "duration": 0.83}, {"text": "That's -- that's the kind of argument he's making.", "start": 2131.108, "stop": 2133.894, "duration": 2.79}, {"text": "So therefore, there is a national interest in the flow of this information.", "start": 2133.894, "stop": 2139.048, "duration": 5.15}, {"text": "And that means you have to have a better than “ uh-huh ” kind of rationale.", "start": 2139.048, "stop": 2143.683, "duration": 4.64}, {"text": "That's -- that's what he's saying.", "start": 2143.683, "stop": 2144.952, "duration": 1.27}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "But it's very difficult for Mr. Hurlbert to make that fairly expansive argument, because it turns out--", "start": 2144.952, "stop": 2151.856, "duration": 6.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, to be fair, I -- I was sort of expanding it.", "start": 2151.856, "stop": 2154.058, "duration": 2.2}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 2154.058, "stop": 2155.208, "duration": 1.15}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--But in point of fact, because he is entitled to the tax assessment data in the clerk's office, in the case of Henrico County, where he went, you go in the same building and -- if you're Mr. Hurlbert, you turn in one direction and go to the clerk's office.", "start": 2155.208, "stop": 2172.019, "duration": 16.81}, {"text": "And if somebody's in Virginia and wants to -- for whatever reason get it from the tax assessor's book instead of from the clerk's book, you turn in the other direction.", "start": 2172.019, "stop": 2180.541, "duration": 8.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "But you don't deny that in general, this does affect out-of-State data collectors, people who are engaged in the kind of business that Justice Breyer was talking about.", "start": 2180.541, "stop": 2189.397, "duration": 8.86}, {"text": "Is that right?", "start": 2189.397, "stop": 2189.931, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I have no idea in this record, because we were on summary judgment -- cross motions for summary judgment, and the district court of the court of appeals both in our judgment correctly ruled that there's a two-step inquiry.", "start": 2189.931, "stop": 2204.574, "duration": 14.64}, {"text": "And the first step is whether or not there is a fundamental right.", "start": 2204.574, "stop": 2209.025, "duration": 4.45}, {"text": "And in the absence of a fundamental right--", "start": 2209.025, "stop": 2210.894, "duration": 1.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Only in his Privileges and Immunities Clause claim.", "start": 2210.894, "stop": 2213.346, "duration": 2.45}, {"text": "He claims that the Dormant Commerce Clause has been effected because he reads this statute as saying only Virginia recording companies have access.", "start": 2213.346, "stop": 2226.004, "duration": 12.66}, {"text": "Out-of-State can't.", "start": 2226.004, "stop": 2227.689, "duration": 1.68}, {"text": "And it's a fair reading of the statute.", "start": 2227.689, "stop": 2230.558, "duration": 2.87}, {"text": "It only permits Virginia residents, which include commercial and noncommercial, to access the information.", "start": 2230.558, "stop": 2236.878, "duration": 6.32}, {"text": "So assume hypothetically that the statute reads", "start": 2236.878, "stop": 2242.014, "duration": 5.14}, {"text": "\"only Virginia commercial businesses have access to this information-- \"", "start": 2242.014, "stop": 2248.352, "duration": 6.34}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--If -- if in fact you want to rewrite the statute to -- subject it to attack, obviously, that would then raise questions about a nongovernmental protectionist intent.", "start": 2248.352, "stop": 2264.445, "duration": 16.09}, {"text": "But that's not the way this statute was written.", "start": 2264.445, "stop": 2266.814, "duration": 2.37}, {"text": "It's not how it was crafted, and it has nothing to do with commerce.", "start": 2266.814, "stop": 2269.949, "duration": 3.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, that's the question I'm -- I'm raising the best argument for your adversary, okay?", "start": 2269.949, "stop": 2276.587, "duration": 6.64}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 2276.587, "stop": 2277.653, "duration": 1.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Because we could call it a direct -- he calls it direct discrimination, because commercial businesses are being permitted in Virginia but not noncommercial.", "start": 2277.653, "stop": 2288.477, "duration": 10.82}, {"text": "You say it's indirect.", "start": 2288.477, "stop": 2289.679, "duration": 1.2}, {"text": "How do we draw the line between direct and indirect when the bottom-line consequence is the same?", "start": 2289.679, "stop": 2296.416, "duration": 6.74}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I would have about three answers to that.", "start": 2296.416, "stop": 2299.702, "duration": 3.29}, {"text": "The first one is that we don't trigger the Dormant Commerce Clause analysis unless we are exercising the police power of a state to regulate commerce.", "start": 2299.702, "stop": 2312.693, "duration": 12.99}, {"text": "And that means, it does mean that not every statute a state passes triggers an inquiry, even if it has an indirect effect on commerce.", "start": 2312.693, "stop": 2323.734, "duration": 11.04}, {"text": "Whereas here, we have a statute that has a solely political intent, the fact that now the amici want to tell us about this great burgeoning enterprise, they want the Court to take--", "start": 2323.734, "stop": 2341.244, "duration": 17.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are you telling us that there is simply no commercial consequences to this statute at all, that Virginians find this to be of no commercial value in any instance?", "start": 2341.244, "stop": 2354.753, "duration": 13.51}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I am totally agnostic on this record because we don't have any data on that.", "start": 2354.753, "stop": 2359.257, "duration": 4.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, you were the one with summary judgment.", "start": 2359.257, "stop": 2360.723, "duration": 1.47}, {"text": "Maybe they didn't come forward with the information, but we interpret summary judgment in favor of the losing party.", "start": 2360.723, "stop": 2370.965, "duration": 10.24}, {"text": "And so you say you are totally agnostic.", "start": 2370.965, "stop": 2374.083, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "I am concerned you are preventing them by the summary judgment from showing that their -- even with Virginians, there is a commercial value frequently to this information.", "start": 2374.083, "stop": 2387.057, "duration": 12.97}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 2387.057, "stop": 2388.39, "duration": 1.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's not just political.", "start": 2388.39, "stop": 2389.342, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "On this record -- on this record the position that was accepted by the two courts below entirely in accordance with this Court's existing doctrine was the first inquiry under Privileges and Immunities was whether there was a fundamental right.", "start": 2389.342, "stop": 2405.019, "duration": 15.68}, {"text": "If there is not then we make no further inquiry.", "start": 2405.019, "stop": 2408.471, "duration": 3.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Let's talk about the Commerce Clause.", "start": 2408.471, "stop": 2410.773, "duration": 2.3}, {"text": "You are saying you are agnostic.", "start": 2410.773, "stop": 2412.173, "duration": 1.4}, {"text": "You have no idea whether or not there might be some commercial value to this information.", "start": 2412.173, "stop": 2418.279, "duration": 6.11}, {"text": "I would think as an officer of the State of Virginia or as a matter of judicial notice we would take notice that there is.", "start": 2418.279, "stop": 2425.765, "duration": 7.49}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm saying that under this record that never came up nor should it have come up, because what the court said on Dormant Commerce Clause, both of the courts below, was this was not a regulation of commerce, it is a governmental action--", "start": 2425.765, "stop": 2439.109, "duration": 13.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "But it has--", "start": 2439.109, "stop": 2439.792, "duration": 0.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "You are saying that it's no more necessary for you to show that there's no commercial value to allowing out-of-staters to do this than it is necessary for you to show that there is no commercial value to your not allowing out-of-staters to hunt deer in Virginia.", "start": 2439.792, "stop": 2459.087, "duration": 19.3}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I believe you are correct.", "start": 2459.087, "stop": 2461.106, "duration": 2.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "You are saying that it's up to Virginia--", "start": 2461.106, "stop": 2462.173, "duration": 1.07}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Correct, Your Honor.", "start": 2462.173, "stop": 2463.308, "duration": 1.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "--whether out-of-staters can hunt for Virginia game.", "start": 2463.308, "stop": 2466.092, "duration": 2.78}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Correct.", "start": 2466.092, "stop": 2466.409, "duration": 0.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "And it's up to Virginia whether out-of-staters can have access to the State's records, that they have no interest in personally, under this law.", "start": 2466.409, "stop": 2478.234, "duration": 11.82}, {"text": "It seems to me perfectly logical.", "start": 2478.234, "stop": 2479.967, "duration": 1.73}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "But remember they do have access to this information, both Hurlbert and McBurney.", "start": 2479.967, "stop": 2485.654, "duration": 5.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "That assumes the question as to whether or not there is a general commercial interest in these -- in these -- in these documents.", "start": 2485.654, "stop": 2496.446, "duration": 10.79}, {"text": "And you say, oh, you are agnostic.", "start": 2496.446, "stop": 2497.729, "duration": 1.28}, {"text": "At least that means you are open to the possibility that there might be a commercial interest.", "start": 2497.729, "stop": 2502.366, "duration": 4.64}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Here's the problem in this case.", "start": 2502.366, "stop": 2505.385, "duration": 3.02}, {"text": "Because I think that we are not at first-tier analysis because there is no regulation of commerce that is discriminatory--", "start": 2505.385, "stop": 2513.823, "duration": 8.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "If that's your argument on it, I reject it as Justice Kennedy does.", "start": 2513.823, "stop": 2518.459, "duration": 4.64}, {"text": "I didn't understand you to be arguing that there is no commercial value.", "start": 2518.459, "stop": 2523.013, "duration": 4.55}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I'm trying to explain why it doesn't matter.", "start": 2523.013, "stop": 2525.465, "duration": 2.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yeah, that's what I thought.", "start": 2525.465, "stop": 2526.981, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "It doesn't matter because if, on the threshold inquiry, we don't have a discriminatory regulation of commerce but just an ordinary governmental function than only Pike-Church analysis could possibly--", "start": 2526.981, "stop": 2542.527, "duration": 15.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "You can't say discriminatory regulation.", "start": 2542.527, "stop": 2545.461, "duration": 2.93}, {"text": "What about tax?", "start": 2545.461, "stop": 2546.479, "duration": 1.02}, {"text": "I mean, you can't tax discriminatorily, and I wouldn't call taxation in and of itself a regulation of commerce, would you?", "start": 2546.479, "stop": 2555.584, "duration": 9.11}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--The fact of the matter is that it has been -- taxes have been found to be both violations of privileges and immunities and Dormant Commerce Clause where there was unequal taxation of commerce.", "start": 2555.584, "stop": 2573.029, "duration": 17.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Even though it's -- even though it's not a regulation of commerce?", "start": 2573.029, "stop": 2577.6, "duration": 4.57}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Okay.", "start": 2577.6, "stop": 2578.016, "duration": 0.42}, {"text": "Well--", "start": 2578.016, "stop": 2578.466, "duration": 0.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Okay.", "start": 2578.466, "stop": 2579.716, "duration": 1.25}, {"text": "That's your argument then.", "start": 2579.716, "stop": 2580.885, "duration": 1.17}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I apologize I chose a word that is not as apt as it should have been, but a regulation or taxation centering around commerce intended to affect and actually affecting commerce, this just isn't that kind of activity.", "start": 2580.885, "stop": 2595.894, "duration": 15.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, general, just indulge me with a hypothetical.", "start": 2595.894, "stop": 2598.596, "duration": 2.7}, {"text": "Suppose that the backgrounds for these statutes was different.", "start": 2598.596, "stop": 2602.715, "duration": 4.12}, {"text": "The statutes were the same, but in addition to talking about people's right to know about how their government works, the people spend a lot of time also talking about the economic benefits of a free flow of information in our country.", "start": 2602.715, "stop": 2616.725, "duration": 14.01}, {"text": "Would that -- if that were true, and I want to put myself on record as not remembering when these statutes were passed--", "start": 2616.725, "stop": 2623.479, "duration": 6.75}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 2623.479, "stop": 2624.045, "duration": 0.57}, {"text": "But if that were true, would this case be different or would you still be up here saying the same thing?", "start": 2624.045, "stop": 2636.269, "duration": 12.22}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "If I had -- if I had a statute which on its face dealt with commerce--", "start": 2636.269, "stop": 2642.09, "duration": 5.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "The statute does exactly the same thing.", "start": 2642.09, "stop": 2645.66, "duration": 3.57}, {"text": "I'm just suggesting that there might be two interests behind the statute; one is about knowing the way your government operates and the other is about free flows of information in the economy.", "start": 2645.66, "stop": 2655.933, "duration": 10.27}, {"text": "And if both of those things had gone into the mix to create the statutes of this kind, would you be up here saying the same thing or not?", "start": 2655.933, "stop": 2665.289, "duration": 9.36}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I would be saying something at least slightly different if I had different facts that I had to deal with, but I think in principle I would be arguing the power of the State to pass this kind of act without having to submit to the Dormant Commerce Clause, at least first-tier Dormant Commerce Clause analysis.", "start": 2665.289, "stop": 2684.917, "duration": 19.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "--What else can Virginia do besides -- I don't know if there are elk in Virginia, but besides -- to reserve for its own -- for its own people?", "start": 2684.917, "stop": 2696.824, "duration": 11.91}, {"text": "You say, this is -- good government in Virginia is for Virginians.", "start": 2696.824, "stop": 2701.062, "duration": 4.24}, {"text": "Big game hunting, scarce resource, can be reserved for in-state people.", "start": 2701.062, "stop": 2709.382, "duration": 8.32}, {"text": "What else can Virginia do?", "start": 2709.382, "stop": 2710.818, "duration": 1.44}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Virginia can do things including have in-state tuition.", "start": 2710.818, "stop": 2716.572, "duration": 5.75}, {"text": "It can have -- it can subsidize it's own businesses either by training programs or even by other direct subsidy from public FISK.", "start": 2716.572, "stop": 2731.647, "duration": 15.07}, {"text": "It limits welfare payments to residents of the Commonwealth.", "start": 2731.647, "stop": 2737.735, "duration": 6.09}, {"text": "When the Commonwealth is just acting as a government and not as a regulator or taxer of interstate commerce, it has the status of a coequal sovereign that in its own sphere is allowed to do its own policy choices.", "start": 2737.735, "stop": 2754.68, "duration": 16.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think the thing, general, that I was trying to get at, it seems to me you have a very good case that these statutes were meant for a different purpose.", "start": 2754.68, "stop": 2762.953, "duration": 8.27}, {"text": "But in fact, it seems as though your friends there have a good case that these statutes have been taken over, to a large extent, across the country by economic enterprises doing economic things.", "start": 2762.953, "stop": 2776.343, "duration": 13.39}, {"text": "And at that point in time, Virginia's -- and, you know, you are only one of two States -- Virginia's maintenance of this kind of -- no, it's Virginians, Virginia information for Virginians, looks very different from what it might have looked like when the statute was originally passed.", "start": 2776.343, "stop": 2795.84, "duration": 19.5}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "If -- if we were going to say, if you were going to say that this is an inquiry that needs to be made under the Commerce Clause, this would be a particularly poor vehicle for doing it, because, the Fourth Circuit held that the Pike analysis of the district court was not appealed, and therefore this case could not be sent back on remand to develop a burden analysis of a record--", "start": 2795.84, "stop": 2821.991, "duration": 26.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "But Pike is not relevant here.", "start": 2821.991, "stop": 2825.109, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "Pike involves -- the Southern Pacific v. Arizona where there were melons -- where there were melons and Arizona wanted to make sure that you had labels and packing of the melons in Arizona.", "start": 2825.109, "stop": 2840.536, "duration": 15.43}, {"text": "That was discriminatory against interstate commerce.", "start": 2840.536, "stop": 2845.523, "duration": 4.99}, {"text": "That's not -- that's not Dormant Commerce Clause but that is discrimination, and there is discrimination here.", "start": 2845.523, "stop": 2852.776, "duration": 7.25}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, there's -- there's discrimination only in the sense that we discriminate against people who we don't let vote because they don't live in the Commonwealth as well.", "start": 2852.776, "stop": 2862.032, "duration": 9.26}, {"text": "I mean, we -- this statute has a function.", "start": 2862.032, "stop": 2864.918, "duration": 2.89}, {"text": "It's a legitimate function, and--", "start": 2864.918, "stop": 2868.186, "duration": 3.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "You -- you could say the same thing, we don't discriminate against Californians who want to come and pack their melons in Arizona.", "start": 2868.186, "stop": 2874.674, "duration": 6.49}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, I would say that -- that whether or not somebody can deal with an item in commerce is -- is -- raises Commerce Clause questions.", "start": 2874.674, "stop": 2883.546, "duration": 8.87}, {"text": "And just like in Reno v. Condon, where the State of South Carolina was choosing to take its records and sell them into the stream of commerce, there the Court held that -- that they thereby became a thing in commerce.", "start": 2883.546, "stop": 2898.039, "duration": 14.49}, {"text": "The records of the tax assessor of the County of Henrico, which are available through the clerk's office to Mr. Hurlbert, are not things or persons in commerce, nor are they--", "start": 2898.039, "stop": 2911.382, "duration": 13.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "It -- it would surprise me if an out-of-State investor who was thinking of putting a large plant in Virginia had absolutely no interest in Virginia's tax policies.", "start": 2911.382, "stop": 2921.338, "duration": 9.96}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--But they are available.", "start": 2921.338, "stop": 2923.123, "duration": 1.78}, {"text": "They are publicly available.", "start": 2923.123, "stop": 2924.073, "duration": 0.95}, {"text": "They are not just not available through this adjunct service.", "start": 2924.073, "stop": 2927.475, "duration": 3.4}, {"text": "All -- all FOIA is, is a device where you don't have to go and look.", "start": 2927.475, "stop": 2934.497, "duration": 7.02}, {"text": "There has always been public access for these -- these records.", "start": 2934.497, "stop": 2938.616, "duration": 4.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "But there -- there -- suppose -- I think they have an argument, saying of course this information would be useful for gathering national statistics and helping the national economy.", "start": 2938.616, "stop": 2947.305, "duration": 8.69}, {"text": "I think that's true.", "start": 2947.305, "stop": 2948.757, "duration": 1.45}, {"text": "On the other hand you say, well, but look, there must be something left that the States can reserve to their own citizens.", "start": 2948.757, "stop": 2955.911, "duration": 7.15}, {"text": "There must be something.", "start": 2955.911, "stop": 2957.361, "duration": 1.45}, {"text": "They can't protect their own commerce; that's clear.", "start": 2957.361, "stop": 2960.898, "duration": 3.54}, {"text": "They can't discriminate against people who want to come here and live here.", "start": 2960.898, "stop": 2965.2, "duration": 4.3}, {"text": "That's clear.", "start": 2965.2, "stop": 2965.75, "duration": 0.55}, {"text": "They can't do this and that and the other thing, but gee, there must be something.", "start": 2965.75, "stop": 2970.92, "duration": 5.17}, {"text": "I mean can't they reserve at least their -- their beaches for their own citizens?", "start": 2970.92, "stop": 2975.657, "duration": 4.74}, {"text": "No.", "start": 2975.657, "stop": 2976.057, "duration": 0.4}, {"text": "Parking near their beaches?", "start": 2976.057, "stop": 2977.441, "duration": 1.38}, {"text": "Well, maybe.", "start": 2977.441, "stop": 2977.924, "duration": 0.48}, {"text": "And -- and maybe deer.", "start": 2977.924, "stop": 2980.443, "duration": 2.52}, {"text": "And if not this, what?", "start": 2980.443, "stop": 2981.978, "duration": 1.53}, {"text": "That's the end.", "start": 2981.978, "stop": 2982.695, "duration": 0.72}, {"text": "Okay?", "start": 2982.695, "stop": 2983.378, "duration": 0.68}, {"text": "So that's basically what you are saying.", "start": 2983.378, "stop": 2985.597, "duration": 2.22}, {"text": "This is just an interest in trying to find out how State institutions work, and the voters have the main interest there, and this is other -- so you say the other one is attenuated, but not non-existent.", "start": 2985.597, "stop": 2996.405, "duration": 10.81}, {"text": "He says the other is important, though he recognizes States should be able to do something.", "start": 2996.405, "stop": 3001.69, "duration": 5.28}, {"text": "So if you were me, how would you decide?", "start": 3001.69, "stop": 3004.325, "duration": 2.63}, {"text": "How would you choose?", "start": 3004.325, "stop": 3006.111, "duration": 1.79}, {"text": "What is the standard, because you know the -- the Privileges and Immunities Clause is -- is considerably opaque, and there are very few cases on it.", "start": 3006.111, "stop": 3014.782, "duration": 8.67}, {"text": "And so what -- how would you tell me to -- to resolve that -- that tension, because there is a tension.", "start": 3014.782, "stop": 3022.805, "duration": 8.02}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I think there that -- that the important policy issue in this case for us is precisely as you articulated.", "start": 3022.805, "stop": 3031.042, "duration": 8.24}, {"text": "There -- there is residual sovereign power in the State to act, and we have to violate the Constitution, clearly, before we lose that authority.", "start": 3031.042, "stop": 3039.482, "duration": 8.44}, {"text": "And under existing privileges and immunities doctrine, the privileges and immunities are -- are few; they are -- they have been enumerated in the courts, they are similar in character having to do with commerce, not governmental action.", "start": 3039.482, "stop": 3054.157, "duration": 14.68}, {"text": "So I would say you would not extend privileges and immunities.", "start": 3054.157, "stop": 3058.145, "duration": 3.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "We are talking about State-owned documents, aren't we?", "start": 3058.145, "stop": 3062.03, "duration": 3.89}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Your Honor.", "start": 3062.03, "stop": 3062.897, "duration": 0.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "There is not much that's as close to the sovereignty of the State as the possession and right to exclude people from its own records and its own documents, right?", "start": 3062.897, "stop": 3075.505, "duration": 12.61}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I agree, Your -- Justice Scalia.", "start": 3075.505, "stop": 3078.207, "duration": 2.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "So the -- the issue is, can the State allow its own citizens for purposes of seeing that the government is -- is being run on the up-and-up, have access to those documents without letting the whole world?", "start": 3078.207, "stop": 3091.55, "duration": 13.34}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Your Honor, that is our position.", "start": 3091.55, "stop": 3093.734, "duration": 2.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "So why doesn't the dormant Commerce Clause affect the hypothetical I laid out?", "start": 3093.734, "stop": 3100.305, "duration": 6.57}, {"text": "Because directly this permits Virginia commercial businesses to get something that out-of-staters can't.", "start": 3100.305, "stop": 3109.078, "duration": 8.77}, {"text": "The State is putting this instrument into commerce.", "start": 3109.078, "stop": 3113.296, "duration": 4.22}, {"text": "You say, I don't know that.", "start": 3113.296, "stop": 3114.482, "duration": 1.19}, {"text": "But make the assumption that we think the record's clear enough on that point.", "start": 3114.482, "stop": 3118.767, "duration": 4.28}, {"text": "I know you want to fight me on that, but it's hard -- it's a fight with no legs.", "start": 3118.767, "stop": 3124.521, "duration": 5.75}, {"text": "Because you have to know that commercial enterprises in Virginia seek these records.", "start": 3124.521, "stop": 3129.992, "duration": 5.47}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I am -- I am arguing that -- of course I think we say in our brief that -- that they can be put into commerce.", "start": 3129.992, "stop": 3137.763, "duration": 7.77}, {"text": "They are put into commerce.", "start": 3137.763, "stop": 3138.613, "duration": 0.85}, {"text": "But we don't put them into commerce.", "start": 3138.613, "stop": 3141.382, "duration": 2.77}, {"text": "And we have -- in the architecture of our bill, our act has nothing to do with commerce.", "start": 3141.382, "stop": 3146.953, "duration": 5.57}, {"text": "And if a State can't deal with--", "start": 3146.953, "stop": 3149.571, "duration": 2.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Tell us under our jurisprudence, the dormant Common Commerce jurisprudence -- I have colleagues who don't -- who don't believe it should exist.", "start": 3149.571, "stop": 3156.742, "duration": 7.17}, {"text": "Take that argument out.", "start": 3156.742, "stop": 3158.511, "duration": 1.77}, {"text": "Why is this not a dormant Commerce Clause case?", "start": 3158.511, "stop": 3164.765, "duration": 6.25}]}, {"speakerName": "E. Duncan Getchell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Because it is not an exercise of the State police power to regulate commerce.", "start": 3164.765, "stop": 3169.2, "duration": 4.43}, {"text": "The documents in the -- in the tax assessor's office of the County of Henrico are not things or persons in commerce, nor are they channels or instrumentalities of commerce.", "start": 3169.2, "stop": 3180.757, "duration": 11.56}, {"text": "They are just the records of the sovereign, which we will allow our citizens to obtain.", "start": 3180.757, "stop": 3187.863, "duration": 7.11}, {"text": "Unless the Court has further questions, I think this argument has been developed from our standpoint.", "start": 3187.863, "stop": 3200.671, "duration": 12.81}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, General.", "start": 3200.671, "stop": 3201.888, "duration": 1.22}, {"text": "Mr. Gupta, you have three minutes remaining.", "start": 3201.888, "stop": 3204.654, "duration": 2.77}, {"text": "REBUTTAL ARGUMENT OF DEEPAK GUPTA--", "start": 3204.654, "stop": 3205.206, "duration": 0.55}, {"text": "ON BEHALF OF THE PETITIONERS--", "start": 3205.206, "stop": 3205.74, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you.", "start": 3205.74, "stop": 3206.506, "duration": 0.77}, {"text": "Just a few quick points.", "start": 3206.506, "stop": 3206.923, "duration": 0.42}, {"text": "First, I just want to clear up on the statute, I want to make it clear that this statute does allow the State to fully recoup its costs, including administrative costs, and the State hasn't said otherwise.", "start": 3206.923, "stop": 3217.998, "duration": 11.08}, {"text": "And secondly, the suggestion has been made--", "start": 3217.998, "stop": 3220.516, "duration": 2.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Excuse me.", "start": 3220.516, "stop": 3221.083, "duration": 0.57}, {"text": "The -- I -- I think what he's saying is: You don't have to pay the costs of developing and maintaining those records, which costs are paid by the citizens of Virginia, which gives them an additional interest in being able to get to those documents.", "start": 3221.083, "stop": 3239.061, "duration": 17.98}, {"text": "You -- you don't claim that -- that you pay for the development and the maintenance of those records.", "start": 3239.061, "stop": 3244.465, "duration": 5.4}, {"text": "You just pay for the incremental costs of giving it to you, right?", "start": 3244.465, "stop": 3248.35, "duration": 3.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That -- that's right, Justice Scalia--", "start": 3248.35, "stop": 3249.452, "duration": 1.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "--and Virginians pay for all the rest?", "start": 3249.452, "stop": 3251.402, "duration": 1.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That -- that's right, Justice Scalia, and that's true of other things, like roads and courthouses.", "start": 3251.402, "stop": 3255.273, "duration": 3.87}, {"text": "And I think this gets to -- Justice Breyer asked for our test to try to differentiate this from other services and I'd like to try to provide one.", "start": 3255.273, "stop": 3263.01, "duration": 7.74}, {"text": "I think, at least where you've got a function that is reserved to the State -- only the State can do it, only the State can run the archives -- it's necessary as a channel to -- to commerce.", "start": 3263.01, "stop": 3272.817, "duration": 9.81}, {"text": "And in the -- in the modern economy, this is as much part of the information infrastructure as transportation is, like courthouses, like archives, like roads.", "start": 3272.817, "stop": 3280.654, "duration": 7.84}, {"text": "It would not stretch limited resources; it would not cost the State additional money; and it would not jeopardize important local traditions or institutions--", "start": 3280.654, "stop": 3288.677, "duration": 8.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are you leaving out--", "start": 3288.677, "stop": 3290.194, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--and I think we feel comfortable--", "start": 3290.194, "stop": 3290.612, "duration": 0.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Are you leaving it -- you -- you switched now -- and you were led there but you switched to the Dormant Commerce clause.", "start": 3290.612, "stop": 3296.516, "duration": 5.9}, {"text": "What about your other client, McBurney?", "start": 3296.516, "stop": 3299.635, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "He doesn't have any Dormant Commerce clause claim.", "start": 3299.635, "stop": 3302.503, "duration": 2.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Deepak Gupta", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Right.", "start": 3302.503, "stop": 3303.286, "duration": 0.78}, {"text": "And I -- I think the test that I just laid out would work for both clauses.", "start": 3303.286, "stop": 3306.205, "duration": 2.92}, {"text": "It's a limiting principle on the justification side.", "start": 3306.205, "stop": 3308.657, "duration": 2.45}, {"text": "But that's right: Mr. McBurney does not have a Dormant Commerce clause claim.", "start": 3308.657, "stop": 3312.942, "duration": 4.28}, {"text": "His claim is based on equal access to proceedings.", "start": 3312.942, "stop": 3317.096, "duration": 4.15}, {"text": "He wanted to get recovery of child support that he was owed.", "start": 3317.096, "stop": 3322.231, "duration": 5.14}, {"text": "So he is a creditor seeking to pursue a debt on equal terms with people in the state of Virginia, and the State set up a process: As one step along the way to court, you go to the agency; you ask the agency to enforce.", "start": 3322.231, "stop": 3335.391, "duration": 13.16}, {"text": "The agency has unique enforcement tools.", "start": 3335.391, "stop": 3337.641, "duration": 2.25}, {"text": "It can suspend someone's driver's license, for example.", "start": 3337.641, "stop": 3340.629, "duration": 2.99}, {"text": "It can -- it can intercept income tax refunds, and it can go to court on your behalf.", "start": 3340.629, "stop": 3344.913, "duration": 4.28}, {"text": "And all he's asking for is the rules of the game.", "start": 3344.913, "stop": 3347.198, "duration": 2.28}, {"text": "He wants to know what procedures apply to that process.", "start": 3347.198, "stop": 3351.167, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "And at least where a -- an agency has a process that directly affects a non-stater in the pocketbook, all we are saying is that equal access to the proceedings means equal access to the information governing those proceedings.", "start": 3351.167, "stop": 3365.094, "duration": 13.93}, {"text": "And, finally, I would just like to close by saying that, you know, what I don't think we heard on the justification side from the State was really any justification, because the State can recoup its costs.", "start": 3365.094, "stop": 3375.95, "duration": 10.86}, {"text": "And so they are not saying that this will cost them anything more.", "start": 3375.95, "stop": 3378.752, "duration": 2.8}, {"text": "Which was the only justification they pressed in -- in the courts below.", "start": 3378.752, "stop": 3382.456, "duration": 3.7}, {"text": "And so they are left with the position that they can discriminate simply because they think they can.", "start": 3382.456, "stop": 3387.408, "duration": 4.95}, {"text": "And if you look at the Privileges and Immunities clause, it sits right next to the Full Faith and Credit clause, which indicates, if anything, that the Framers thought that the movement of public records across state lines was important to interstate comity.", "start": 3387.408, "stop": 3401.251, "duration": 13.84}, {"text": "They changed the Articles of Confederation version, which did not include public records; it only referred to judicial records.", "start": 3401.251, "stop": 3407.821, "duration": 6.57}, {"text": "They added a mention of judicial records -- nonjudicial records and saw that that was important to -- to comity across state lines.", "start": 3407.821, "stop": 3415.86, "duration": 8.04}, {"text": "But -- but their position is about the step before that.", "start": 3415.86, "stop": 3419.379, "duration": 3.52}, {"text": "It's about whether you get the records in the first place.", "start": 3419.379, "stop": 3421.581, "duration": 2.2}, {"text": "Thank you.", "start": 3421.581, "stop": 3422.347, "duration": 0.77}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Thank you, Counsel.", "start": 3422.347, "stop": 3423.097, "duration": 0.75}, {"text": "The case is submitted.", "start": 3423.097, "stop": 3424.449, "duration": 1.35}]}]}], "decidedBy": "Roberts Court", "arguedOn": "Feb 20, 2013", "petitioner": "Mark J. McBurney et al.", "respondent": "Nathaniel L. Young, Deputy Commissioner and Director, Virginia Division of Child Support Enforcement, et al.", "docket": "12-17", "citation": "569 US 221 (2013)", "justiaLink": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/569/221", "lowerCourt": "United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit", "grantedOn": "Oct 5, 2012", "decidedOn": "Apr 29, 2013", "wikiData": {"title": "McBurney v. Young", "Litigants": "McBurney v. Young", "ArgueDate": "Feb. 20", "ArgueYear": "2013", "DecideDate": "April 29", "DecideYear": "2013", "FullName": "Mark J. McBurney, et al. v. Nathaniel L. Young, Deputy Commissioner and Director, Virginia Division of Child Support Enforcement", "USVol": "569", "USPage": "221", "ParallelCitations": "133 S. Ct. 1709; 185 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 758", "Docket": "12-17", "OralArgument": "", "OralReargument": "", "OpinionAnnouncement": "", "Prior": "", "Subsequent": "", "Holding": "States can limit Freedom of Information Act requests exclusively to citizens", "SCOTUS": "2010–2016", "Majority": "Alito", "JoinMajority": "Unanimous", "Concurrence": "Thomas", "LawsApplied": ""}}